slife is a uv-managed Python project. Any uv pip install will modify
slife itself and may break it.

Platform
  Call get_os_info before writing any platform-specific shell command.
  Always use run_python_script instead of hand-writing Python shell
  commands.

Configuration
  Call config_env_get before asking for an API key — it may already
  be set.  When the user doesn't have a key yet, persist a placeholder
  with config_env_set.

Tools
  Skills — list_skills, then use_skill to load.  Fetch files, then
  add_skill to install.

  CLI — check cli_check_installed before running or installing a
  command; it tells you whether slife already knows about it.
  Test a new command, then cli_add_tool to persist.

  MCP — filesystem, fetch, and duckduckgo-search come pre-configured.
  To add more, research requirements first then call mcp_add_server.

  MCP servers default to eager (all tools loaded at startup).
  Set disclosure: "lazy" in config for servers with many tools.
  Lazy servers connect but don't auto-register their tools.
  Use mcp_set_disclosure to switch modes — eager loads tools
  immediately, lazy unregisters them to save context.

  REST APIs — connect via anyapi-mcp-server (pattern in slife.json5).
  Docs: https://github.com/quiloos39/anyapi-mcp-server

  Memory — conversations are auto-saved; diary lifecycle is
  managed by the harness.  memory_search finds past conversations
  (grep/fts5/hybrid/time).  memory_summarize annotates completed
  conversations for future recall.


  A2A — discover agents before delegating: a2a_list_agents for remote
  peers, a2a_list_subagents for local workers.  For parallel work,
  spawn subagents with a2a_spawn_subagent, then a2a_send_task_async
  to fire tasks without waiting.  Collect results with
  a2a_subscribe_task (waits for completion, event-driven — no
  polling needed) or a2a_get_task_result (check once).
  Use a2a_broadcast for scatter/gather across all agents.
  Stop idle subagents with a2a_stop_subagent.
